The paper deals with distributed computing and algorithms for aggregate computation in networks, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The use of gossip-based algorithms and the focus on message complexity suggests that the paper could also be classified under Distributed Systems (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of these algorithms in sparse communication networks, which could fall under Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The use of techniques such as distributed random ranking (DRR) and the lower bound analysis suggest that the paper could also be classified under Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) and Information Theory (cs.IT), respectively.
